Introduction

For this project, you will explore the question of whether the Affordable Care Act increased health insurance coverage (or conversely, decreased the number of people who are uninsured). The ACA was passed in March 2010, but several of its provisions were phased in over a few years. The ACA instituted the “individual mandate” which required that all Americans must carry health insurance, or else suffer a tax penalty. There are four mechanisms for how the ACA aims to reduce the uninsured population:

  • Require companies with more than 50 employees to provide health insurance.
  • Build state-run healthcare markets (“exchanges”) for individuals to purchase health insurance.
  • Provide subsidies to middle income individuals and families who do not qualify for employer based coverage.
  • Expand Medicaid to require that states grant eligibility to all citizens and legal residents earning up to 138% of the federal poverty line. The federal government would initially pay 100% of the costs of this expansion, and over a period of 5 years the burden would shift so the federal government would pay 90% and the states would pay 10%.

In 2012, the Supreme Court heard the landmark case NFIB v. Sebelius, which principally challenged the constitutionality of the law under the theory that Congress could not institute an individual mandate. The Supreme Court ultimately upheld the individual mandate under Congress’s taxation power, but struck down the requirement that states must expand Medicaid as impermissible subordination of the states to the federal government. Subsequently, several states refused to expand Medicaid when the program began on January 1, 2014. This refusal created the “Medicaid coverage gap” where there are indivudals who earn too much to qualify for Medicaid under the old standards, but too little to qualify for the ACA subsidies targeted at middle-income individuals.

States that refused to expand Medicaid principally cited the cost as the primary factor. Critics pointed out however, that the decision not to expand primarily broke down along partisan lines. In the years since the initial expansion, several states have opted into the program, either because of a change in the governing party, or because voters directly approved expansion via a ballot initiative.

You will explore the question of whether Medicaid expansion reduced the uninsured population in the U.S. in the 7 years since it went into effect. To address this question, you will use difference-in-differences estimation, and synthetic control.

Data

The dataset you will work with has been assembled from a few different sources about Medicaid. The key variables are:

  • State: Full name of state
  • Medicaid Expansion Adoption: Date that the state adopted the Medicaid expansion, if it did so.
  • Year: Year of observation.
  • Uninsured rate: State uninsured rate in that year.

  • Estimates a difference-in-differences estimate of the effect of the Medicaid expansion on the uninsured share of the population. You may follow the lab example where we estimate the differences in one pre-treatment and one post-treatment period, or take an average of the pre-treatment and post-treatment outcomes.

Answer: The Diff-in-Diff estimate of the effect on Medicaid expansion on the unisured share of the population is 0.039675.

# Filtering the data for the states and years specified
mt <- Montana2 %>%
  filter(State %in% c("Montana", "New York")) %>%
  filter(year >= 2008 & year <= 2020)

# Pre-treatment difference
pre_diff <- mt %>%
  filter(year == 2008) %>%
  dplyr::select(State, uninsured_rate) %>%  #
  tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = State, values_from = uninsured_rate) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(difference = `New York` - Montana)

# Post-treatment difference
post_diff <- mt %>%
  filter(year == 2020) %>%
  dplyr::select(State, uninsured_rate) %>%  # Use dplyr::select to avoid any conflicts
  tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = State, values_from = uninsured_rate) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(difference = `New York` - Montana)

# Difference-in-Differences calculation
diff_in_diffs <- post_diff$difference - pre_diff$difference

# Print result
diff_in_diffs
## [1] 0.039675

Discussion Questions

  • Card/Krueger’s original piece utilized the fact that towns on either side of the Delaware river are likely to be quite similar to one another in terms of demographics, economics, etc. Why is that intuition harder to replicate with this data?

  • Answer:

This intuition is harder to replicate with this data because states are not as homogeneous as towns located close to each other. States can vary significantly in terms of their political economy, and thus, state-level data likely captures larger, more systemic variations that do not precisely mirror the conditions of neighboring states, even if they share a border.

  • What are the strengths and weaknesses of using the parallel trends assumption in difference-in-differences estimates?

  • Answer: There are several strengths associated with using the parallel trends assumption in diff-in-diff estimates. First, the assumption is fairly intuitive–units that follow the same trajectory over time will probably continue to do so until a treatment is administered. Additionally, by assuming that any differences in trends between treated and control groups are due to the treatment, diff-in-diff effectively controls for all time-invariant confounders. On the other hand, the parallel trends assumption can be very difficult to fully satisfy, as any pre-treatment variation between the control and treated groups can be viewed as violation of the rule (although researchers do give some leeway towards the extent to which these groups can vary pre-treatment).

Synthetic Control

Estimate Synthetic Control

Although several states did not expand Medicaid on January 1, 2014, many did later on. In some cases, a Democratic governor was elected and pushed for a state budget that included the Medicaid expansion, whereas in others voters approved expansion via a ballot initiative. The 2018 election was a watershed moment where several Republican-leaning states elected Democratic governors and approved Medicaid expansion. In cases with a ballot initiative, the state legislature and governor still must implement the results via legislation. For instance, Idaho voters approved a Medicaid expansion in the 2018 election, but it was not implemented in the state budget until late 2019, with enrollment beginning in 2020.

Discussion Questions

  • What are the advantages and disadvantages of synthetic control compared to difference-in-differences estimators?

  • Answer: Besides controlling for unobserved heterogeneity, the largest advantage of synthetic controls over diff-in-diff estimators is that they are less dependent on the parallel trends assumption because they use a combination of control units rather than a single unit that mirrors the pre-treatment characteristics of the treated unit. This is particularly helpful for comparative political economists who focus on American institutions, which are difficult to find comparative (e.g. parallel) cases to in Europe and North America. The biggest disadvantage of synthetic controls compared to diff-in-diff estimators is that in order to effectively create a synthetic control, it is often necessary to have access to a long time series of data before the intervention.

  • One of the benefits of synthetic control is that the weights are bounded between [0,1] and the weights must sum to 1. Augmentation might relax this assumption by allowing for negative weights. Does this create an interpretation problem, and how should we balance this consideration against the improvements augmentation offers in terms of imbalance in the pre-treatment period?

  • Answer: Personally, I find negative weights to be counterintuitive because they imply that some control units within the synthetic control have a “negative presence”; rather than simply contributing less influence, they are actually detracting from or opposing the influence of other units. I think the best way to balance this consideration is by including both the average ATT, L2 imbalance, and percent improvement from uniform weights, from both augmented and non-augmented synthetic controls.

General Discussion Questions

  • Why are DiD and synthetic control estimates well suited to studies of aggregated units like cities, states, countries, etc?

  • Answer: Diff-in-Diff and synthetic control estimates are well suited to model changes in aggregated units because both are able to, to varying extents, control for unobserved confounders, which become a greater issue as you begin to aggregate units that are not exactly alike. So long a the parallel-trends assumption holds, a typical Diff-in-Diff may be sufficient in controling for unobserved confounders because the difference between the treated and control groups would have remained constant over time. This allows DiD to effectively estimate the causal impact of an intervention by comparing the changes in outcomes over time between the treated and control groups. In cases where the parallel-trends assumption is not satisfied, synthetic controls can be used to create a counterfactual control case by combining other units using weights.

  • What role does selection into treatment play in DiD/synthetic control versus regression discontinuity? When would we want to use either method?

  • Answer: Both diff-in-Diff and synthetic control assume that, without the treatment, the outcomes for treated and control groups would have followed parallel paths over time. Pre-existing differences between these groups or unobserved confounders are stable over time and do not interact with the treatment effect. This is useful in cases where random selection is unfeasible; the parallel trends assumption mitigates the biases introduced by unobserved confounders. Selection into treatment plays a different role in regression discontinuity, where assignment is determined by a specific threshold or rule, which creates a quasi-randomization at the threshold. For example, if a scholarship (treatment) is administered to students who score at least 85/100 on an exam, the students just above the threshold (who scored an 85 or 86 on the exam) are likley very similar to those just below the threshold (who scored an 83 or 84). This similarity allows us to assume that any significant differences in outcomes between these two groups can be attributed to the scholarship, rather than other variables that might otherwise differentiate students further away from the threshold. Diff-in-Diff and synthetic control are ideally used when analyzing the effects of interventions over time across multiple units without a clear, predefined assignment rule, whereas regression discontinuity design is more useful when treatment assignment is strictly defined by a specific threshold.
